                          imgCredit:'Ian Duffy, CC BY 2.0',
                          name:'Emperor penguin',latin:'Aptenodytes forsteri',era:'Eocene',
                          desc:'The tallest and heaviest of all living penguin species, endemic to Antarctica. It has black head and back plumage sharply contrasting with a white belly, pale-yellow breast, and bright-yellow ear patches.',
                          detail:'Emperor penguins are the only penguin species that breeds during the Antarctic winter, trekking 50-120 km over ice to breeding colonies. The female lays a single egg incubated for over two months by the male while the female returns to sea to feed.',
                          funFact:'Emperor penguins can dive to 535 meters deep — deeper than any other bird — and hold their breath for over 20 minutes by shutting down non-essential organ functions.',
